
#If statements

#If statements allow you to see the current state of the program and see the conditions.
#This chapter will teach you how to write conditional statements.

cars = ['audi','bmw','subaru','toyota']

for car in cars:
  if car == 'bmw':
    print(car.upper())
  else:
    print(car.title())

#Here python checks to see if the current value of car is bmw
#and if it IS then it will print the value in uppercase
#BUT if the value is anything other than bmw then the other values will be printed that are not bmw are printed in title.

#Conditional tests

#At the heart of every if statement, it can be seen as a true/false approach. In the case of python it is called a conditional test.
#meaning it will determine if the conditions are met and should be executed.
#When the condition is true, the code will execute, and if it is false then the code will be ignored.

